Durban - Nosiviwe Mapisa-Nqakula, National Minister of Defence and Military Veterans, is set to join at least 29 other defence ministers at the VII Moscow Conference on International Security (MCIS) taking place from April 3 - 5, 2018.

At the conference, Mapisa-Nqakula will meet her Russian counterpart Sergey Shoygu, where the two ministers will discuss a variety of bilateral defence issues. ADVERTISINGinRead invented by Teads

This year the MCIS will, inter alia, pay particular attention to terrorism in Syria, including security issues facing Europe, Asia, Africa and Latin America.

Launched by the Russian Ministry of Defence in 2012, the MCIS has long played an important role in global and regional security affairs, bringing together Defence Ministers, government officials and security experts from around the world.

It is estimated that the seventh instalment of the conference will bring together delegates from 95 countries. According to the Russian Ministry of Defence, 30 Defence Ministers from around the globe have confirmed their participation, as well as members of eight international organisations and 68 foreign security experts.

